Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel!). Trim the @cucumber{1/2}. Use a #vegetable peeler{} to peel long ribbons from all sides of the length of the cucumber. Stop when you get to the seeds (discard the seeds). Trim the @carrot{1}. Use a vegetable peeler to peel long ribbons from all sides of the length of the carrot. Stop when you can't peel anymore (and have the rest of the carrot as a pre-dinner snack!).

Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, then season with @salt{1/4%salt} and @black pepper{to taste}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Put the @rice vinegar{30}ml, @sugar{1} level tbsp, @water{2} tbsp and @salt{1} tsp in a #small saucepan{} over medium heat. Stir and cook until the sugar and salt have dissolved, ~{1-2%minutes}. Put the cucumber and carrot ribbons in a #bowl{}. Pour over the pickling liquid and toss to coat. Set aside.

Zest the @lime{1/2}, cut into wedges. Put the @mayonnaise{1} tbsp in a bowl, squeeze in half the lime juice. Set aside. Finely chop the @coriander{1}(finely chopped) (stalks and all). Pop the @Thai style spice mix{1/2} in a bowl and add the lime zest, @pork sausage meat{225%g} and half the coriander. Mix together with your hands until combined. Wet your hands and shape into 5 balls per person.

> The Thai spice is quite spicy - adjust amount to taste. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Heat a drizzle of @oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat, once hot, add the meatballs and fry until golden on the outside and cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}. Turn every ~{2%minutes} and turn the heat down if necessary.

> The meat is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the meatballs cook, halve the @brioche hot dog buns{2} lengthways down the middle (but not the whole way through). Pop them into the oven for the last ~{2%minutes} of wedge cooking time to warm through.

Add the remaining coriander to the carrot and cucumber and mix together. Spread a spoonful of mayo on the bottom of each bun and top with the meatballs. Finish with a little of the pickle (but leave the liquid in the bowl). Serve the sausage banh-mi on plates with the remaining pickle alongside, the wedges and the remaining mayo to dip your chips in. Finish with lime wedges and enjoy!